<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[192,1440,705,858]" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,351,705,729]" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species is distinctive in the group by having the forewing costal area abruptly broadened near the base (
<figureCitation box="[517,590,738,762]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="11.[193,289,1845,1867]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,558,1816]" captionTargetId="figure-201@11.[192,1440,558,1817]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figures 1–7. Purenleon abruptus Stange, adult. 1) head and thorax; 2) lateral view; 3) vertex; 4) wings; 5) male genitalia; 6) female terminalia, ventral view; 7) female terminalia, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5179533" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5179533/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The midfemoral sense hair is about one-half as long as that of the forefemur, about one-fourth length of femur. The larva differs from others in the inscriptus group in having a prominent row of dolichasters posterior to the lateral tentorial suture which is duplicated in the bistictus group by 
<emphasis box="[467,968,834,858]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miller and Stange Ventral" authorityYear="2014" box="[467,589,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Purenleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apache">P. apache</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[600,725,834,857]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Purenleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aztecus">P. aztecus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[737,834,834,857]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Purenleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cavei">P. cavei</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gerstaecker" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[846,962,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Purenleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilis">P. debilis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1154,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Purenleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="toltecus">
<emphasis box="[1028,1154,834,858]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">P. toltecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[192,1440,898,954]" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,348,898,922]" pageId="13" pageNumber="12">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the costal area of forewing which is abruptly narrowed near the base.
</paragraph>
